Sorcerers inherit the Chromatic Circle tradition, a pre-academic order of arcanists who rejected emerging universities and their narrow specializations, holding that the deepest power lies in synthesis — fire and ice together, healing and destruction from the same hand. The Circle's foundational insight was that breadth is methodology rather than dilettantism: the interactions between spell schools are precisely the phenomena most resistant to single-school analysis and most important to understand. The Confluence Texts documented every observed interaction between spell schools organized by interaction type — resonance, interference, amplification, cancellation — representing the Circle's equivalent of the Axiomatic Schools' formal proofs, applied to phenomena the Schools had explicitly excluded from their methodology as unverifiable under single-school conditions. The Axiomatic Schools' response — that unverifiable by single-school practitioners doesn't mean unreal — was technically correct and institutionally ineffective: the academies controlled credential recognition, research funding, and publication access, and eventually absorbed or outlawed most Circle branches. The tradition survived in small apprentice chains, with the Confluence Texts preserved selectively, each chain maintaining portions most relevant to the elemental schools its practitioners worked in. Modern Sorcerer practice is organized around the elemental doctrine derived from the most consistently preserved Confluence content: four primary elemental schools (fire, air/lightning, water, earth) and their documented interaction effects. The stormbinder tradition — multi-school elemental synthesis applied to atmospheric phenomena — produced the Ash-and-Iron Decades intervention that redirected ash-laden storm fronts from destabilized Cinderteeth Mountains, creating the institutional moment for the Grand Magi title to be reclaimed. The Grand Magi adept synthesis combines Sorcerer breadth with Wizard precision, vindicating the Confluent Theorists' Convergence Codices.

